25|$|During {{colonial times}} the cuisines of the British Isles were the {{standard}} {{in most areas}} of Tasmania. Tasmania now has {{a wide range of}} restaurants, in part due to the arrival of immigrants and changing cultural patterns. Scattered across Tasmania are many vineyards, and Tasmanian beer brands such as Boags and Cascade are known and sold in Mainland Australia. King Island off the northwestern coast of Tasmania has a reputation for boutique cheeses and dairy products. Tasmanians are also consumers of seafood, such as crayfish, <b>orange</b> <b>roughy,</b> salmon and oysters, both farmed and wild.|$|E
