50|$|Due to its longevity, the <b>orange</b> <b>roughy</b> accumulates {{large amounts}} of mercury in its tissues,3 having a range of 0.30-0.86 ppm {{compared}} with an average mercury level of 0.086 ppm for other edible fish. Based on average consumption and the recommendations of a National Marine Fisheries Service study, in 1976, the FDA set the maximum safe mercury level for fish at 1 ppm. Regular consumption of <b>orange</b> <b>roughy</b> can have adverse effects on health. Compared to most edible fish, <b>orange</b> <b>roughy</b> are a very poor source of omega-3 fatty acids, averaging less than 3.5 g/kg.|$|E
